{"kind":"cannot-formalise","why":"winsomely is an adverbial modifier (manner adverb) derived from the adjective winsome, which expresses a qualitative aesthetic-emotional judgment about how an action or appearance affects an observer (charming, appealing, engaging in a gentle or innocent way). The core semantic content—a subjective evaluation of charm or attractiveness—does not decompose into the prime predicates and substantives available in the lexicon. While one could attempt to ground it via FEEL (someone feels something good when they see/hear X), that loses the specific connotations of gentle charm, innocence, and social appeal that distinguish winsome from merely pleasing. The concept belongs to the affective-aesthetic domain and requires cultural/subjective grounding that the kernel primes cannot provide in a gate-legal way."}
